Here's the full solution:

**1. The converter** — `Converters/OrderStatusToColorConverter.cs`

```csharp
using System.Globalization;

namespace MyApp.Converters;

public class OrderStatusToColorConverter : IValueConverter
{
    public object? Convert(object? value, Type targetType,
        object? parameter, CultureInfo culture)
    {
        if (value is OrderStatus status)
        {
            return status switch
            {
                OrderStatus.Pending   => Colors.Orange,
                OrderStatus.Shipped   => Colors.Blue,
                OrderStatus.Delivered => Colors.Green,
                OrderStatus.Cancelled => Colors.Red,
                _ => Colors.Gray
            };
        }
        return Colors.Gray;
    }

    public object? ConvertBack(object? value, Type targetType,
        object? parameter, CultureInfo culture)
        => throw new NotSupportedException();
}
```

**2. Wire it up in XAML**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             xmlns:vm="clr-namespace:MyApp.ViewModels"
             xmlns:converters="clr-namespace:MyApp.Converters"
             x:DataType="vm:OrderViewModel">

    <ContentPage.Resources>
        <converters:OrderStatusToColorConverter x:Key="StatusToColor" />
    </ContentPage.Resources>

    <Label Text="{Binding Status}"
           TextColor="{Binding Status, Converter={StaticResource StatusToColor}}" />

</ContentPage>
```

**Key points:**

- `x:DataType` is set at the page root for compiled bindings (8–20× faster, AOT-safe).
- The converter returns `Colors.*` values directly — `TextColor` expects a `Color`.
- `ConvertBack` throws `NotSupportedException` since this is display-only.
- `FallbackValue` / `TargetNullValue` can be added if `Status` might be null:
  ```xml
  TextColor="{Binding Status, Converter={StaticResource StatusToColor},
              FallbackValue=Gray}"
  ```
